1- We were in the debugger, and gave a "wrong" command, ie the command
   "i" that lead to an error. The first thing is that this should not
   make the debugger quit.  A debugging state embodied by a
   invoke-debugger invocation, may represent a lot of processing time,
   and should not be dropped unless the user explicitely requests it.
   So all errors should be handled properly from the debugger (and
   navi/sedit/inspect on the interactor stack) so that we don't leave
   the debugger.

2- We need a general error handling. The fact that the same error is
   signaled by the same form (* 2 nil), doesn't matter much. If we had
   given a jump command to a poll-point that would signal immediately an
   error, we'd be in the same situation: we should be back in the
   debugger (with a new invoke-debugger call I suppose). So I think
   the problem here is that it's the clautolisp layer that caught the error a
   a time where the debugger is not ready to re-enter. This path shouldn't exist
   (or rather it should exist for last-ressort case, but when aldo is installed
   it should be invoked).
   
        clautolisp: runtime error: INVALID-NUMBER-ARGUMENT: * expects a number, got NIL.
        AutoLISP backtrace (most recent call first, 22 frames):


* Resolution (1.4.38)

1. =r= takes a *mandatory* expression (AutoLISP has no multiple values /
   no-value — every function returns something): a bare =r= now prompts
   =return value?= and reads it from the debugger input; a blank answer or
   EOF cancels the command. =h= documents =r FORM=.

2. The unwind in the transcript: at an *error stop*, =i=/=n=/=o= (and
   =a=/=j=) produced a step/advance/jump directive that
   APPLY-ERROR-DIRECTIVE does not recognise, which silently *declined* the
   stop and let the error propagate to the toplevel handler. These commands
   now refuse at an error stop with the §10.1 guidance (=q= abort, =r FORM=
   return a value, =c= continue/run =*error*=) and the command loop keeps
   reading — the debugging state is only dropped by an explicit =q=/abort.

3. General error handling while debugging: the command dispatcher
   (DISPATCH-IN-DICTIONARIES, the single choke point through which every
   built-in / user / mode command body runs) now catches errors escaping a
   command, reports =error while executing CMD=, and keeps the stop. An
   AutoLISP error signaled *while a command evaluates user code* still
   re-enters the debugger first — the session's §10 HANDLER-BIND is
   installed around the whole turn and runs before any unwind — giving the
   nested invoke-debugger the issue asks for; whatever the user lets
   propagate from that nested stop is then caught at the dispatcher and the
   outer stop survives. The clautolisp toplevel runtime-error report remains
   as the last resort — reached only when the user explicitly declines an
   error stop (=c= with no =*error*= set), which is its specified meaning.

Tests: bare-r-prompts-for-the-return-value,
step-at-an-error-stop-does-not-quit-the-debugger,
a-failing-command-keeps-the-debugger-alive (dumb-ui suite, 415/415).
